Notices for chaoscontrol/kernels/_ssm_scan
===========================================

Upstream projects (algorithmic reference only — no code copied)
---------------------------------------------------------------

1. Flash Linear Attention (FLA), https://github.com/sustcsonglin/flash-linear-attention,
   licensed under the MIT License. The recurrence we compute —
   ``state[t] = decay[t] * state[t-1] + update[t]`` — is mathematically
   identical to HGRN's ``h[t] = exp(g[t]) * h[t-1] + x[t]`` with
   ``g = log(decay)``. We read ``fla/ops/hgrn/fused_recurrent.py`` for the
   overall structure (per-channel tiling, T-chunk loop) but wrote a fresh
   CUDA C++ kernel — FLA's reference is Triton, and we own the stack here.

2. Mamba (state-spaces), https://github.com/state-spaces/mamba, licensed
   under the Apache License, Version 2.0. A copy of that license text is
   preserved in ``LICENSE_UPSTREAM`` as required by §4(a) for any derivative
   work. We read ``csrc/selective_scan/selective_scan_fwd_kernel.cuh`` for
   the block-tile / CUB BlockScan idiom, but:
     * Mamba's math is selective (per-timestep delta + B/C projections);
       ours is plain per-channel diagonal scan.
     * Our current shipping kernel uses the naive per-thread serial loop
       layout, NOT the BlockScan chunk carry. The Mamba-style approach was
       evaluated as an optimization path and parked when the naive kernel
       already beat the torch.compile baseline at our submission shape
       (B=1024, T=512, D=256).

Scope of derivation
-------------------
No upstream source files were copied or translated line-for-line. The
design of this extension's public API, pybind11 bindings, build hook,
CUDA kernel, and Python wrapper is first-party. Both upstream projects
are acknowledged for informing the approach.

If we later port the Mamba-style chunked BlockScan kernel and it crosses
"informed by" into "derived from" (copied kernel structure, shared lookup
tables, ported device functions), we will add the upstream copyright
header to the affected file alongside an explicit "Modifications:" note
per Apache 2.0 §4(b).
